'National Premier Leagues Victoria Women''', known commonly as the '''NPL Victoria Women's''' or '''NPLV Women's''', is a semi-professional women's association football league in [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], [[Australia]]. It is the highest league for women in Victoria, and has been a part of the [[National Premier Leagues Women\u2019s]] structure, and which is administered by [[Football Victoria]]. Prior to the introduction of the NPL in Victoria in 2016, the league was known as the Women's Victorian Premier League.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ozfootball.net/ark/States/VIC/2016WNPLT.html|title=Women's National Premier Leagues Victoria \u2013 Final Table|website=www.ozfootball.net|access-date=2019-04-12}}</ref> \n\nThe league is contested by ten clubs, playing a 27 round season, with the regular season running from February to September. The finals series is contested between the top four clubs, with the top two playing against third and fourth in a semi-final and the winners contesting the grand final. There is no promotion and relegation from the WNPL. \n\n== WNPL Years (2016\u2013present) ==\nThe initial members of the WNPL were Alamein, Bayside United, [[FC Bulleen Lions|Bulleen Lions]], [[Box Hill United SC|Box Hill United]], Calder United, [[Heidelberg United FC|Heidelberg United]], Geelong Galaxy United, Senior NTC and Southern United. <ref name=\":0\" /> In the following season, [[South Melbourne FC|South Melbourne]] was admitted to the league who went on to win the inaugural Finals Series, 5\u20134 on penalties against Geelong Galaxy United.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ozfootball.net/ark/States/VIC/2017WNPLR.html|title=- Season Results|website=www.ozfootball.net|access-date=2019-04-12}}</ref> South Melbourne again made the Grand Final the following season losing 3\u20131 to Bulleen Lions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://websites.sportstg.com/comp_info.cgi?c=0-10178-0-479810-0&a=ROUND|title=Results for NPL Women VIC|website=SportsTG|language=en|access-date=2019-04-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.footballvictoria.com.au/news/heidelberg-and-bulleen-champions-npl-victoria|title=Heidelberg and Bulleen Champions of NPL Victoria|website=Football Victoria|language=en|access-date=2019-04-12}}</ref> Despite not being crowned Champions, South Melbourne were successful in the regular season who were crowned Premiers of the 2018 season. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://websites.sportstg.com/comp_info.cgi?c=0-10178-0-479810-0&a=LADDER|title=Ladder for NPL Women VIC|website=SportsTG|language=en|access-date=2019-04-12}}</ref> This was a feat achieved by the club as well in their initial season in the renewed league.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://websites.sportstg.com/comp_info.cgi?c=0-10178-0-435506-0&a=LADDER|title=Ladder for PS4 NPL VIC Women|website=SportsTG|language=en|access-date=2019-04-12}}</ref> Calder United were crowned Grand Final Champions for the second time defeating Bulleen Lions 1\u20130.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://beyond90.com.au/npl/vic-nplw-grand-final-match-report/|title=VIC NPLW Grand Final \u2013 Match Report|last=Downes|first=Cheryl|date=2019-09-15|website=Beyond 90|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-30}}</ref> This was after Calder were crowned league champions prior to the finals series.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://websites.sportstg.com/comp_info.cgi?c=0-10178-0-513760-0&a=LADDER|title=Ladder for NPL VIC Women|website=SportsTG|language=en|access-date=2019-10-30}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"5\" |'''Women's National Premier Leagues Victoria'''\n|-\n! Season\n! Grand Final Champions \n! GF Runners Up \n! League Premiers\n! League Runners Up\n|-\n|[[2019 Football Federation Victoria season#2019 NPL Victoria Women|2019]]\n|[[Keilor Park SC|Calder United]]\n|[[FC Bulleen Lions|Bulleen Lions]]\n|[[Keilor Park SC|Calder United]]\n|[[FC Bulleen Lions|Bulleen Lions]]\n|-\n|[[2018 Football Federation Victoria season#2018 Women's National Premier League|2018