{"title_page": "Mark Gatiss", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n | name         = Mark Gatiss\n | image        = Mark Gatiss by Gage Skidmore 2.jpg\n | caption      = Gatiss in 2017\n | birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1966|10|17}}\n | residence    = [[North London]], England\n | birth_place  = [[Sedgefield]], [[County Durham]], England\n | occupation   = Actor, screenwriter, television producer, comedian, novelist, director\n | years_active = 1993&ndash;present\n | spouse       = {{marriage|[[Ian Hallard]]|2008}}\n | website      = \n | module       = {{Listen \n                   | embed= yes \n                   | filename= Mark_Gatiss_BBC_Radio4_Desert_Island_Discs_23_Oct_2011_b0167vjr.flac \n                   | title= Mark Gatiss's voice \n                   | type= speech \n                   | description= from the BBC programme ''[[Desert Island Discs]]'', 23 October 2011.<ref name=\"BBCr4 DesertIslandDiscs\">\n                   {{Cite episode\n                    | title= Mark Gatiss\n                    | series= Desert Island Discs\n                    | serieslink= Desert Island Discs\n                    | url= http://bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0167vjr\n                    | station= [[BBC Radio 4]]\n                    | date= 23 October 2011\n                    | accessdate= 18 January 2014\n                   }}</ref>\n                  }}\n}}\n\n'''Mark Gatiss''' ({{IPAc-en|audio=Gattis.ogg|\u02c8|g|e\u026a|t|\u026a|s}};<ref name=\"BBCr4 DesertIslandDiscs\" /><ref>{{cite episode | title = Science of Christmas | url = http://downloads.bbc.co.uk/podcasts/radio4/timc/timc_20111226-1700a.mp3 | accessdate = 28 December 2011 | series = The Infinite Monkey Cage | serieslink = The Infinite Monkey Cage | credits = Presented by [[Brian Cox (physicist)|Brian Cox]] and [[Robin Ince]] | network = [[BBC]] | station = [[BBC Radio 4]] | airdate = 26 December 2011 | seriesno = 5 | number = 6 | time = 2:28 | quote = There is still a 49% chance that his name will be mispronounced. So please welcome Mark Gatiss not Gatiss.}}</ref> born 17 October 1966) is an English actor, comedian, screenwriter, director, producer and novelist. His work includes writing for and acting in the TV series ''[[Doctor Who]]'', ''[[Sherlock (TV series)|Sherlock]]'', and ''[[Dracula (2020 TV series) | Dracula]]''. Together with [[Reece Shearsmith]], [[Steve Pemberton]] and [[Jeremy Dyson]], he is a member of the comedy team ''[[The League of Gentlemen]]''. He played [[Tycho Nestoris]] in the [[HBO]] series ''[[Game of Thrones]]''.\n\n==Early life and education==\nGatiss was born in [[Sedgefield]], County Durham,<ref name=guardian2010-10-11>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2010/oct/11/mark-gatiss-first-men-moon |title=Mark Gatiss: Rocket man |date=11 October 2010 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|last=Jeffries|first=Stuart |location=London}}</ref> England, to Winifred Rose (n\u00e9e O'Kane, 1931&ndash;2003) and Maurice Gatiss (b. 1931).<ref>{{cite web|title=Mark Gatiss featured article on TheGenealogist|url=http://www.thegenealogist.co.uk/featuredarticles/2015/who-do-you-think-you-are/mark-gatiss-287/|website=TheGenealogist|accessdate=6 October 2015}}</ref> He grew up opposite the [[Edwardian era|Edwardian]] [[Winterton Hospital|psychiatric hospital]] where his father worked.<ref name=autogenerated1>Mark Lawson Talks to Mark Gatiss</ref> His family background is working class.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> His childhood passions included watching ''[[Doctor Who]]'' and [[Hammer Horror]] films on television, reading [[Sherlock Holmes]] and [[H.G. Wells]], and collecting fossils. One of his early forays into theatre was in the role of Dad in ''The Waiting Room'' by Tony Stowers in Darlington in March 1983, a macabre and surreal Pinteresque comedy exploring a disintegrating family unit. He would have also been in the Stowers follow-up ''A Sense of Insecurity'' also in Darlington in July of the same year but he was unable to take the role because his dad wouldn't allow him to and insisted he take his exams instead <ref>''The Chiseller'' by T Stowers {{ISBN|9781501005046}}).</ref> All of these interests have fuelled his creative work as an adult.<ref name=telegraphgeek /><ref name=sundayherald>{{cite news|title=Renaissance gentleman |author=Stephen Phelan |newspaper=[[The Sunday Herald]] |date=7 November 2004 |accessdate=23 November 2010 |url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4156/is_20041107/ai_n12591433 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090913005720/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4156/is_20041107/ai_n12591433/ |archivedate=13 September 2009 }}</ref><ref name=guardian2004>{{cite news |title=A league of his own |author=Angelique Chrisafis |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=3 November 2004 |accessdate=24 November 2010 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2004/nov/03/fiction.angeliquechrisafis |location=London}}</ref><ref name=leagueofgentlemen>{{cite web |title=Film Info. Interview with Steve Pemberton and Mark Gatiss |publisher=[[The League of Gentlemen]].co.uk |date=7 November 2004 |accessdate=24 November 2010 |url=http://www.leagueofgentlemen.co.uk/newopen.shtml }}</ref>\n\nHe attended [[Heighington Church of England Primary School]] and [[Woodham Community Technology College|Woodham Comprehensive School]] in [[Newton Aycliffe]]; at the latter, he was two years ahead of [[Paul Magrs]], who would also go on to write ''Doctor Who'' fiction.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-30117544_ITM |title=Remembering Heighington's past with pride; The headteacher |newspaper=The Northern Echo |date=26 March 2007 |quote=One Heighington alumnus is actor Mark Gatiss, the star of hit comedies The League of Gentlemen and Little Britain. |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018080807/http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-30117544_ITM |archivedate=18 October 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Golly goth |first=Steve |last=Pratt |newspaper=[[The Northern Echo]] |date=8 May 2007 |url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/leisure/1383869.Golly_goth/ |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120912035351/http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/leisure/1383869.Golly_goth/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=12 September 2012 |accessdate=25 June 2010 |quote=Coincidentally, another Doctor Who fan and novel writer, The League of Gentlemen's Mark Gatiss also went to Woodhall, where he was two years above Magrs and in the same drama group. }}</ref> He then studied Theatre Arts at [[Bretton Hall College of Education|Bretton Hall College]] which was an arts college affiliated to [[University of Leeds|Leeds University]].<ref name=essential>{{cite book|date=25 March 2011|author=David Leavey|isbn=978-0813125688|title=The Essential Cult TV Reader|publisher=The University Press of Kentucky}}</ref>\n\nGatiss was awarded an honorary doctorate of letters by the University of Huddersfield in 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hud.ac.uk/news/visitors/honorarygraduates/|title=Honorary Graduates - University of Huddersfield|date=24 April 2017|accessdate=29 December 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424011700/https://www.hud.ac.uk/news/visitors/honorarygraduates/|archivedate=24 April 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Acting===\n====''The League of Gentlemen''====\nGatiss is a member of the sketch comedy team [[The League of Gentlemen]] (along with fellow performers [[Reece Shearsmith]], [[Steve Pemberton]] and co-writer [[Jeremy Dyson]]). He first met his co-writers and performers in his late teens at [[Bretton Hall, West Yorkshire|Bretton Hall]], Yorkshire, a drama school which he attended after finishing school and having spent a gap year travelling around Europe.\n\n''The League of Gentlemen'' began as a stage act in 1995, which won the [[Edinburgh Comedy Awards|Perrier Award]] at [[Edinburgh Festival Fringe]] in 1997.<ref name=\"telegraphgeek\" /> In the same year the show transferred to [[BBC Radio 4]] as ''[[On the Town with The League of Gentlemen (radio series)|On the Town with the League of Gentlemen]]'', and later arrived on television on [[BBC Two]] in 1999. The television programme has earned Gatiss and his colleagues a [[British Academy Television Award]], a [[Royal Television Society]] Award and the prestigious [[Golden Rose of Montreux]].\n\nIn 2005, the film ''[[The League of Gentlemen's Apocalypse]]'' was released, to generally positive reviews.<ref name=\"telegraphgeek\" />\n\nShearsmith and Pemberton reunited in 2009 to create a similarly dark BBC sitcom, ''[[Psychoville]]'', which featured an episode guest-starring Gatiss. The three reunited again in 2012 to film a series of sketches for the fourth series of [[CBBC]] show ''[[Horrible Histories (2009 TV series)|Horrible Histories]]''.{{Citation needed|date=February 2018}}\n\n====Other television work====\n[[File:Mark Gatiss at A Scandal in Belgravia screening.png|thumb|252x252px|Mark Gatiss at \"[[A Scandal in Belgravia]]\" episode screening]]\nOutside the League, Gatiss' television work has included writing for the 2001 revival of ''[[Randall and Hopkirk (Deceased) (2000 TV series)|Randall & Hopkirk]]'' and script editing the popular sketch show ''[[Little Britain]]'' in 2003, making guest appearances in both. In 2001 he guested in ''[[Spaced]]'' as a villainous government employee modelled on the character of [[Agent Smith]] from ''[[The Matrix]]'' film series. In the same year he appeared in several editions of the documentary series ''SF:UK''. Other acting appearances include the comedy-drama ''[[In the Red (novel)|In the Red]]'' ([[BBC Two]], 1998), the macabre sitcom ''[[Nighty Night]]'' ([[BBC Three]], 2003), [[Agatha Christie's Marple]] as Ronald Hawes in \"The Murder at the Vicarage\", a guest appearance in the [[Vic & Bob]] series ''[[Catterick (TV series)|Catterick]]'' in 2004 and the live [[The Quatermass Experiment (film)|2005 remake]] of the classic science fiction serial ''[[The Quatermass Experiment]]''. A second series of ''Nighty Night'' and the new comedy-drama ''[[Funland (TV series)|Funland]]'', the latter co-written by his ''League'' cohort [[Jeremy Dyson]], both featured Gatiss and aired on BBC Three in the autumn of 2005. He appeared as [[Johnnie Cradock]], alongside ''Nighty Night'' star [[Julia Davis]] as [[Fanny Cradock]], in ''Fear of Fanny'' on BBC Four in October 2006, and featured as Ratty in a new production of ''[[The Wind in the Willows (2006 film)|The Wind in the Willows]]'' shown on BBC One on 1 January 2007. He wrote and starred in the BBC Four docudrama ''[[The Worst Journey in the World (docudrama)|The Worst Journey in the World]]'', based on the memoir by polar explorer [[Apsley Cherry-Garrard]].\n\nGatiss has also made three credited appearances in ''Doctor Who''. In 2007, he played [[Professor Lazarus]] in \"[[The Lazarus Experiment]]\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/5388130.stm|title=Doctor Who baddie role for Barlow|publisher=[[BBC News Online]]|date=28 September 2006|accessdate=28 September 2006}}</ref> In 2011, he returned in the Series 6 episode \"[[The Wedding of River Song]]\" as a character known as Gantok, and in the 2017 Christmas special \"[[Twice Upon a Time (Doctor Who)|Twice Upon A Time]]\" as \"The Captain\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2017-12-26/doctor-who-christmas-special-cast-plot/|title=Meet the cast of Doctor Who Christmas special 2017 Twice Upon a Time|work=Radio Times|access-date=2018-02-14|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2017/dec/25/doctor-who-christmas-special-2017-twice-upon-a-time|title=Doctor Who Christmas special 2017: Twice Upon a Time|last=Martin|first=Daniel|date=2017-12-25|newspaper=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-02-14}}</ref>\n\nAlso in 2007, he appeared as [[Robert Louis Stevenson]]<ref name=\"echo\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/features/leader/display.var.1082536.0.i_always_wanted_to_be_a_rat.php|title=I Always Wanted to be a Rat|publisher=[[The Northern Echo]]|date=20 December 2006|accessdate=6 January 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927002830/http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/features/leader/display.var.1082536.0.i_always_wanted_to_be_a_rat.php|archivedate=27 September 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref> in ''[[Jekyll (TV serial)|Jekyll]]'', a BBC One serial by his fellow ''Doctor Who'' scriptwriter [[Steven Moffat]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2006/11_november/16/jekyll.shtml|title=Mark Gatiss joins James Nesbitt in BBC One's Jekyll|publisher=[[bbc.co.uk]]|date=16 November 2006|accessdate=16 November 2006}}</ref> In 2008, he appeared in ''[[Clone (TV series)|Clone]]'' as Colonel Black.\n\nIn 2010, he portrayed [[Malcolm McLaren]] in the BBC drama ''[[Worried About the Boy]]'' which focused on the life and career of [[Boy George]], and also appeared as [[Mycroft Holmes]] in the BBC drama ''[[Sherlock (TV series)|Sherlock]]'', which he co-created with [[Steven Moffat]]. He adapted [[H.G. Wells]]' ''[[The First Men in the Moon]]'' into a [[The First Men in the Moon (2010 film)|television film of the same name]] for the BBC, also playing Professor Cavor.<ref name=guardian2010-10-11 /><ref>[http://www.heraldscotland.com/arts-ents/film-tv-features/a-moonstruck-mark-gatiss-sends-hg-wells-into-orbit-1.1060842 Moonstruck Mark Gatiss Sends H.G. Wells Into Orbit] Herald Scotland \u2013 October 2010</ref> He also made a three-part BBC documentary series entitled ''[[A History of Horror]]'', a personal exploration of the history of horror cinema.<ref name=horrorqa>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00vcwm7 |title=A History of Horror with Mark Gatiss \u2013 Q&A with Mark Gatiss |accessdate=12 November 2010 |publisher=BBC }}</ref> This was followed on 30 October 2012 with a look at [[European horror]] with the documentary ''[[Horror Europa]]''.<ref>{{cite web|author=Mark Gatiss |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2012/horror-europa.html |title=Media Centre \u2013 Mark Gatiss returns to BBC Four to tell story of European horror cinema |publisher=BBC |date=1 January 1970 |accessdate=12 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 December 2013, a version of the ghost story \"[[The Tractate Middoth]]\" by [[M. R. James]] and adapted by Gatiss was broadcast on [[BBC2]] as part of the long-running ''[[A Ghost Story for Christmas]]'' series. It starred [[Sacha Dhawan]], [[John Castle]], [[Louise Jameson]], [[Una Stubbs]], [[David Ryall]], [[Eleanor Bron]], [[Nicholas Burns (actor)|Nick Burns]] and [[Roy Barraclough]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Jones |first=Paul |url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2013-12-03/mark-gatiss-lands-christmas-day-treble-on-bbc2 |title=The Tractate Middoth and An Adventure in Space and Time to air on Christmas Day on BBC2 |publisher=Radiotimes.com |date=3 December 2013 |accessdate=12 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Daly |first=Emma |url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2013-09-05/mark-gatiss-casts-sherlocks-una-stubbs-in-festive-ghost-story |title=Mark Gatiss casts Sherlock's Una Stubbs in festive ghost story |publisher=Radio Times |date=5 September 2013 |accessdate=12 January 2014}}</ref> It was followed on 25 December 2013 by a screening on BBC2 of a new documentary by Gatiss titled ''M. R. James: Ghost Writer''. The programme saw Gatiss explore the work of James and look at how his work still inspires contemporary horror today.\n\nHe appeared in [[Game of Thrones (season 4)|season four]] of ''[[Game of Thrones]]'' in 2014 playing [[List of Game of Thrones characters#People of Essos|Tycho Nestoris]]{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}} and reprised this role in [[Game of Thrones (season 5)|season five]] and [[Game of Thrones (season 7)|season seven]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/WatchersOTWall/status/512662231285112832 |title=Mark Gatiss returning for Game of Thrones season 5 |publisher=Watchers On The Wall |date=27 August 2014 |accessdate=10 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the BBC's 2015 series ''[[Wolf Hall (miniseries)|Wolf Hall]]'', Gatiss played [[King Henry VIII]]'s secretary [[Stephen Gardiner]]. He also appeared in Channel 4's ''Coalition'' in 2015.<ref>Carole Cadwalladr, [https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2015/may/01/mark-gatiss-doctor-who-is-my-first-love-baftas-2015-television Mark Gatiss: \u2018Doctor Who is my first love, my last, my everything\u2019], The Guardian, 1 May 2015.</ref>\n\nGatiss appears as the [[George IV of the United Kingdom|Prince Regent (later George IV)]] in the eight-part [[historical fiction]] [[television drama series]] ''[[Taboo (2017 TV series)|Taboo]]'' (2017)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.express.co.uk/showbiz/tv-radio/753182/Taboo-Sherlock-star-Mark-Gatiss-George-VI-Tom-Hardy-drama-BBC|title=Taboo: First look at unrecognisable Sherlock star Mark Gatiss in Tom Hardy's gritty drama|last=Meechan|first=Lauren|date=2017-01-12|work=Express.co.uk|access-date=2018-02-14|language=en}}</ref> first broadcast on [[BBC One]] in the United Kingdom on 7 January 2017 and in the United States on [[FX (TV channel)|FX]] on 10 January 2017.\n\nHe appeared as a modern-day incarnation/descendant of Count Dracula's servile companion [[Renfield]] in the series of his own co-creation, [[Dracula_(2020_TV_series)|Dracula]] in the third and final episode, \"The Dark Compass\".\n\n====Radio, stage and film====\nGatiss appears frequently in [[BBC Radio]] productions, including the science fiction comedy ''[[Nebulous]]'' and ''[[The Further Adventures of Sherlock Holmes]]'' story ''[[The Shameful Betrayal of Miss Emily Smith]]''. In 2009, he was [[BBC Radio 4 Extra|The Man in Black]] when BBC Radio 7 revived the character (originally played by [[Valentine Dyall]] and [[Edward de Souza]]) to introduce a series of five creepy audio dramas. He is also involved with theatre, having penned the play ''The Teen People'' in the early 1990s, and appeared in a successful run of the play ''[['Art' (play)|'Art']]'' in 2003 at the [[Whitehall Theatre]] in London. In film, he has starred in ''[[Sex Lives of the Potato Men]]'' (2004) and had minor roles in ''[[Birthday Girl]]'' (2001), ''[[Bright Young Things (film)|Bright Young Things]]'' (2003), ''[[Match Point]]'' (2005) and ''[[Starter for 10 (film)|Starter for 10]]'' (2006). ''[[The League of Gentlemen's Apocalypse]]'', a film based on the television series, co-written by and starring Gatiss, was released in June 2005. He also plays the recurring character of [[The Passenger (Sapphire and Steel)|Gold]] in the audio revival of ''[[Sapphire and Steel]]'' produced by [[Big Finish Productions]]. Gatiss also appeared in [[Edgar Wright]]'s fake trailer for [[Grindhouse (film)|Grindhouse]], ''[[Don't (grindhouse film)|Don't]]'', a homage to '70s Hammer Horrors.\n[[File:Mark Gatiss.jpg|thumb|left|Gatiss in 2006|210x210px]]\nIn the 2008 English language re-release of the cult 2006 Norwegian animated film ''[[Free Jimmy]]'', Gatiss voiced the character of \"Jakki,\" a heavy-set, bizarrely dressed biker member of the \"Lappish Mafia.\" In this his voice is used along with the other actors of ''League of Gentlemen'' such as Steve Pemberton and Reece Shearsmith. The dialogue was written by [[Simon Pegg]] and other actors included Pegg himself, [[Woody Harrelson]] and [[David Tennant]], who worked with Gatiss on ''Doctor Who''.\n\nHe appeared in the stage adaptation of [[Pedro Almod\u00f3var]]'s ''[[All About My Mother]]'' at the [[Old Vic]] in London from 25 August-24 November 2007. He won much critical acclaim for his portrayal of the transgender character Agrado.\n\nHe was scheduled to perform in ''Darker Shores'' by Michael Punter, a ghost story for all the family, at [[Hampstead Theatre]] 3 December 2009 \u2013 16 January 2010 but had to withdraw after a serious family illness. [[Tom Goodman-Hill]] took over his role.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.watfordobserver.co.uk/leisure/theatre/cfutheatrefeatures/4787207.It___s_on_with_the_show/ |title=It's on with the show (From Watford Observer) |publisher=Watfordobserver.co.uk |date=10 December 2009 |accessdate=28 October 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502183237/http://www.watfordobserver.co.uk/leisure/theatre/cfutheatrefeatures/4787207.It___s_on_with_the_show/ |archivedate=2 May 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2010, he was a guest on ''[[Private Passions]]'', the biographical music discussion programme on [[BBC Radio 3]].<ref name=privatepassions>{{cite web |title=Private Passions |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/radio3/privatepassions |publisher=[[BBC Radio 3]] }}</ref>\n\nFrom December 2010 to March 2011, Gatiss was playing the role of Bernard in [[Alan Ayckbourn]]'s ''Season's Greetings'' at the [[Royal National Theatre]] in London alongside [[Catherine Tate]].\n\nIn December 2011, he appeared in an episode of ''The Infinite Monkey Cage'' in an episode entitled ''The Science of Christmas'', alongside [[Brian Cox (physicist)|Brian Cox]], [[Robin Ince]] and [[Richard Dawkins]].\n\nIn January 2012, he took the role of Brazen in ''[[The Recruiting Officer]]'' at the [[Donmar Warehouse|Donmar Theatre]], London.<ref>{{cite news|last=Shenton|first=Mark|authorlink=Mark Shenton|title=The Recruiting Officer|url=http://www.thestage.co.uk/reviews/review.php/35248/the-recruiting-officer|accessdate=31 December 2012|newspaper=[[The Stage]]|date=15 February 2012}}</ref> From 18 October \u2013 24 November that year he was [[Charles I of England|Charles I]] in the Hampstead Theatre production of ''[[55 Days]]'' by [[Howard Brenton]], a play dramatising the military coup that killed a King and forged a Commonwealth under [[Oliver Cromwell]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Wooley |first=Sarah |url=http://www.hampsteadtheatre.com/whats-on/2012/55-days/ |title=55 Days |publisher=Hampsteadtheatre.com |date= |accessdate=12 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2013, Gatiss joined the cast of the [[Donmar Warehouse]] Production of ''[[Coriolanus (2013 play)|Coriolanus]]'' as Senator of Rome, [[Agrippa Menenius Lanatus (consul 503 BC)|Menenius]]. The play went from 6 December 2013 through 13 February 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=Coriolanus 6 December 2013 \u2013 13 February 2014|url=http://www.donmarwarehouse.com/whats-on/donmar-warehouse/2013/coriolanus|publisher=Donmar Warehouse|accessdate=27 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112204547/http://www.donmarwarehouse.com/whats-on/donmar-warehouse/2013/coriolanus|archive-date=12 November 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> For his role on the play, Gatiss received a [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Actor in a Supporting Role]] nomination.<ref>{{cite news|title=Olivier awards 2014 full list|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2014/mar/10/olivier-awards-2014-full-list-nominations|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=20 April 2014|date=2014-03-10}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2017, Gatiss began a recurring role on \"[http://www.secrethistoryofhollywood.com The Secret History Of Hollywood]\", a series of podcast biopics on Golden Age-era Hollywood. Its 11-part series, '[https://www.attaboyclarence.com/the-secret-history-of-hollywood/ Shadows]' tells the story of [[Val Lewton]]'s life and career, with Gatiss providing the introductions for each episode.\n\nIn November 2018, Gatiss appeared as the lead in a revival of ''[[The Madness of George III]]'' at Nottingham Playhouse.\n\n===Writing===\n\n====''Doctor Who''====\n[[File:Mark Gatiss (9362666697).jpg|thumb|Gatiss at the 2013 [[San Diego Comic-Con]], promoting ''Doctor Who'']]\nAt the age of eleven, Gatiss won a school literary competition with a short science fiction story \"The Anti-Noise Machine\", published in a booklet by Darlington Borough Council.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}} Gatiss had a childhood interest in [[BBC]] science-fiction show ''[[Doctor Who]]'' and devoted much of his early writing to the series, despite its 1989 cancellation. Gatiss's earliest published work as a professional writer was a sequence of novels in Virgin Publishing's [[Virgin New Adventures|New Adventures]] series of continuation stories and novels. In these works, he tried to correct the problems which had led to the show's decline in the late 1980s.<ref name=sundayherald />\n\nThe first television scripts Gatiss wrote were for a [[BBV]] direct-to-video series called \"[[P.R.O.B.E.]]\" Gatiss's four scripts each featured a different actor who had played ''Doctor Who''{{'}}s titular character of [[Doctor (Doctor Who)|the Doctor]]: [[Jon Pertwee]], [[Peter Davison]], [[Colin Baker]] and [[Sylvester McCoy]]. The videos have since been released on DVD despite Gatiss once commenting that he would not authorise their re-release, as he regarded them as a learning exercise.<ref name=sundayherald />\n\nHis other early contributions to the ''Doctor Who'' franchise included four [[Doctor Who spin-offs#Original fiction|novels]], two audio plays for BBV and two audio plays for [[Big Finish Productions]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigfinish.com/28-Doctor-Who-Invaders-from-Mars |title=''Doctor Who \u2013 Invaders From Mars'' |publisher=Bigfinish.com |date= |accessdate=17 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigfinish.com/02-Doctor-Who-Phantasmagoria |title=''Doctor Who \u2013 Phantasmagoria'' |publisher=Bigfinish.com |date= |accessdate=17 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nGatiss has written nine episodes for the 2005 revival of the show. His first, \"[[The Unquiet Dead]],\" was the third episode of the revived series in 2005; the second, \"[[The Idiot's Lantern]],\" aired the following year in the [[Doctor Who (series 2)|second series]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Mark Gatiss Presents Doctor Who Documentary |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/doctorwho/s4/features/bulletins/bulletin_090623_01 | publisher = BBC | accessdate = 17 April 2014 }}</ref> Although he acted in the [[Doctor Who (series 3)|third series]] and proposed an ultimately unproduced episode for the [[Doctor Who (series 4)|fourth]], involving Nazis and the British Museum, it took until 2010 for Gatiss to return as writer. He wrote \"[[Victory of the Daleks]]\" for that year's [[Doctor Who (series 5)|fifth series]] and went on to contribute \"[[Night Terrors (Doctor Who)|Night Terrors]]\" for [[Doctor Who (series 6)|series 6]], \"[[Cold War (Doctor Who)|Cold War]]\" and \"[[The Crimson Horror]]\" for [[Doctor Who (series 7)|series 7]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cultbox.co.uk/features/guides/1954-doctor-who-series-7-news-summary |title='Doctor Who': Series 7 news summary |publisher=Cultbox.co.uk |date=24 April 2013 |accessdate=12 January 2014}}</ref> and \"[[Robot of Sherwood]]\" for [[Doctor Who (series 8)|series 8]]. He also wrote \"[[Sleep No More (Doctor Who)|Sleep No More]]\" for [[Doctor Who (series 9)|series 9]] and \"[[Empress of Mars]]\" for [[Doctor Who (series 10)|series 10]].\n\nHe has also contributed to the franchise outside the main show. His early work (see above) was primarily ''Doctor Who'' expanded media, and Gatiss wrote and performed in the comedy spoof sketches ''The Web of Caves'', ''The Kidnappers'' and ''The Pitch of Fear'' for the BBC's \"[[Doctor Who spoofs|''Doctor Who'' Night]]\" in 1999 with [[David Walliams]].\n\nHe penned 2013 [[docudrama]] ''[[An Adventure in Space and Time]]'', a drama depicting the origins of the series, to celebrate the show's fiftieth anniversary.<ref>{{cite web|last=Mulkern |first=Patrick |url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2013-11-20/mark-gatiss-takes-us-behind-the-scenes-of-doctor-who-drama-an-adventure-in-space-and-time |title=Doctor Who: An Adventure in Space and Time \u2013 Mark Gatiss takes us behind the scenes |publisher=Radiotimes.com |date=20 November 2013 |accessdate=17 April 2014}}</ref> It ended with a cameo by Gatiss's ''[[League of Gentleman]]'' castmate [[Reece Shearsmith]], portraying [[Patrick Troughton]], who played the [[Second Doctor]]. A \"Making Of\" feature about this programme, narrated by Gatiss, was made available on the [[BBC Red Button]] service, and also posted on the [[BBC]]'s official YouTube channel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mLwLV1W2H_c |title=Behind the scenes of An Adventure in Space and Time \u2013 Doctor Who 50th Anniversary \u2013 BBC |publisher=YouTube |date=21 November 2013 |accessdate=17 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nHe has written for ''[[Doctor Who Magazine]]'', including a column written under the pseudonym \"Sam Kisgart,\" which he was originally credited as in the ''[[Doctor Who Unbound]]'' audio play ''[[Sympathy for the Devil (audio drama)|Sympathy for the Devil]]'' for his role as [[Master (Doctor Who)|the Master]]. \"Sam Kisgart\" is an anagram of \"Mark Gatiss\", and is also the name under which he was credited for his cameo in ''Psychoville''.\n\n====''Sherlock''====\nWith [[Steven Moffat]], whom Gatiss worked with on ''Doctor Who'' and ''[[Jekyll (TV series)|Jekyll]]'', he also co-created and co-produced ''[[Sherlock (TV series)|Sherlock]]'', a modernised adaptation of the [[Sherlock Holmes]] stories, in which Gatiss plays the role of Sherlock's brother [[Mycroft Holmes|Mycroft]]. Gatiss has influence on all episodes as producer and he has written four episodes, one for each series: the finale, \"[[The Great Game (Sherlock)|The Great Game]],\" for the first series, \"[[The Hounds of Baskerville]]\" for the second, \"[[The Empty Hearse]]\" for the third and \"[[The Six Thatchers]]\" for the fourth. He also co-wrote \"Many Happy Returns,\" a mini-episode released in late December 2013 which acts as a prelude to the third series, with [[Steven Moffat]]; the episode \"[[The Sign of Three]]\" with Moffat and [[Stephen Thompson (writer)|Steve Thompson]]; and \"[[The Abominable Bride]]\", a special episode released in early January 2016, with Moffat.\n\n====Other work as writer====\nGatiss has written several non-fiction works, including a biography of the film director [[James Whale]] and the documentary ''M.R. James: Ghost Writer'', which Gatiss also presented. The documentary followed Gatiss's directorial debut with an adaption of one of James's stories, \"The Tractate Middoth\", for BBC 2, which was broadcast on Christmas Day 2013. Gatiss also wrote, co-produced and appeared in ''[[Crooked House (TV series)|Crooked House]]'', a ghost story that was broadcast on [[BBC Four]] during Christmas 2008.\n\nHis first non-''Doctor Who'' novel, ''[[The Vesuvius Club]]'', was published in 2004, for which he was nominated in the category of Best Newcomer in the 2006 [[British Book Awards]]. A follow-up, ''[[The Devil in Amber]]'', was released on 6 November 2006. It transports the main character, [[Lucifer Box]], from the [[Edwardian era]] in the first book to the roaring Twenties/Thirties. A third and final Lucifer Box novel, ''[[Black Butterfly (novel)|Black Butterfly]]'', was published on 3 November 2008 by [[Simon & Schuster]].<ref name=simonandschuster>{{cite web|url=http://authors.simonandschuster.com/Mark-Gatiss/28437914 |title=Mark Gatiss \u2013 Official Publisher Page|publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]]|accessdate=17 April 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Gatiss and Steven Moffat re-teamed to write three episodes for TV miniseries ''[[Dracula (2020 TV series)|Dracula]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/sherlock-team-reuniting-for-dracula-series-1202472312/|title='Sherlock' Team Reuniting for New 'Dracula' Series (EXCLUSIVE)|last=Clarke|first=Stewart|date=20 June 2017|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=2 November 2019}}</ref> The series premiered on [[BBC One]] on 1 January 2020, and was broadcast over three consecutive days.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2019-12-03/bbc-dracula-air-date/ |title=BBC\u2019s Dracula will air three days in a row from New Year\u2019s Day |work=RadioTimes |first=Huw |last=Fullerton |date=3 December 2019 |accessdate=4 December 2019}}</ref> The three episodes were then released on [[Netflix]] on 4 January 2020.<ref name=\"trailer-date\">{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/tv/2019/12/13/dracula-premiere-trailers-sherlock-miniseries/|title=Dracula's Netflix premiere awakens in bloody trailers for Sherlock team's miniseries|last=Romano|first=Nick|date=13 December 2019|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=13 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nGatiss is super [[gay]] and was featured on ''[[The Independent on Sunday]]'s'' Pink List of influential gay people in the UK in 2010<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/news/the-iiosi-pink-list-2010-2040472.html|title=The IoS Pink List 2010|publisher=[[The Independent on Sunday]]|date=1 August 2010|accessdate=1 August 2010|quote=The League of Gentlemen star is set for a bonanza 2010. As well as co-creating the BBC's acclaimed Sherlock Holmes reboot, he'll also be seen in his adaptation of HG Wells' ''First Men in the Moon''. An appearance in an Alan Ackybourn revival at the National Theatre is also mooted.|location=London}}</ref> and 2011.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/news/the-iiosi-pink-list-2011-2374595.html |title=The IoS Pink List 2011 | location=London | work=The Independent | first=Ian | last=Herbert | date=23 October 2011}}</ref> He [[Same-sex marriage in the United Kingdom|married]] actor [[Ian Hallard]]<ref>{{cite news | url= https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2016/feb/06/mark-gatiss-interview | title= Q&A: Mark Gatiss \u2013 \u2018Best kiss? My husband, or Ben Whishaw in London Spy' | work=The Guardian | location=London | first=Rosanna | last=Greenstreet | date=6 February 2016 | accessdate=29 August 2016}}</ref> in 2008 in [[Middle Temple]], in the City of London.<ref name=\"Scot interview\">{{cite web |last=Randall |first=Lee |url=http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/features/The-Monday-Interview-Mark-Gatiss.4699282.jp |title=The Monday Interview: Mark Gatiss \u2013 Top of the League \u2013 The Scotsman |publisher=Thescotsman.scotsman.com |date=17 November 2008 |accessdate=28 October 2010 |quote=Amid all this activity, Gatiss found time, last spring, to get married. He and Ian have been together for nearly a decade... He and Ian are the devoted 'parents' of Bunsen, a Labrador retriever. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101126135101/http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/features/The-Monday-Interview-Mark-Gatiss.4699282.jp |archive-date=26 November 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url= https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2010/oct/23/mark-gatiss-family-values | title= Mark Gatiss: My family values | work=The Guardian | location=London | first=Alistair | last=Duncan | date=23 October 2010 | accessdate=27 February 2017}}</ref> Gatiss once built a [[Victorian era|Victorian]] laboratory in his north London home, as the fulfilment of a childhood dream.<ref name=telegraphgeek>{{cite news |title=Mark Gatiss: the journey of a geek made good |author=Michael Deacon |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=15 October 2010 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/bbc/8067325/Mark-Gatiss-the-journey-of-a-geek-made-good.html |location=London}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Actor===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n|1998\u20131999\n|''[[This Morning with Richard Not Judy]]''\n|Various voices\n|Uncredited\n|-\n|1999\u20132002, 2017\n|''[[The League of Gentlemen]]''\n|Various characters\n|also co-creator and co-writer\n|-\n| 2001\n|''[[Spaced]]''\n|Agent<ref name=Agency>{{cite web|title=Mark Gatiss credits|url=http://www.curtisbrown.co.uk/mark-gatiss//works/|publisher=[[Curtis Brown (literary agents)|Curtis Brown]]|accessdate=15 February 2012|location=London}}</ref>\n|\n|-\n| 2001\n|''[[Randall and Hopkirk (Deceased) (2000 TV series)|Randall & Hopkirk]]''\n|Inspector Large<ref name=Agency/>\n|\n|-\n| 